Hi first major surprise as President was on December 9, 2015, when he cancelled a lavish Independence rally and instead said the money set aside for the celebrations should be channeled to hospitals. On that day, he led his country in a massive clean-up the city of Dar es Salaam. 

But it was his crackdown on the media and bloggers that started to indicate that Magufuli was sliding the country towards a dictatorship. New cybercrimes laws that limited freedom of expression were put in place while radio stations and newspapers were closed for “insulting Magufuli”. Insulting the president on social media was made a criminal offence under a cybercrimes law passed in 2015 – just before he came into office. 

In order to tightly control the media, the Magufuli government came up with the Media Services Act of 2016, which designates jail time for sedition. While the East African Court of Justice in March 2019 ruled that sections of the law were in conflict with the East African Community’s treaty, Magufuli ignored the ruling, read by Justice Charles Nyachae of the First Instance Division, and no efforts have been done to rectify the Act. 

His government’s appeal, in the case filed by Media Council of Tanzania, Legal and Human Rights Centre and Tanzania Human Rights Defenders Coalition, was dismissed on a technicality. More so, new electronic and postal communications regulations were enacted in 2018 in order to stymie the growth of blogs and websites. They are now forced to pay heavy registration fees or their owners risk heavy fines and jail terms. 



